Sasalin shot a jet of flame, igniting a small patch of forest, then circled above it, watching for the right moment. Curiously, when he slowed down, the strange shrieking sound behind him also stopped. Sasalin forgot he had a passenger on his back.
"Come on, Tenuk, you've turned into a Slakor before!"
"There's a big difference between flying on your own and being suddenly dragged away by a huge pink dragon!"
"Not bad, Kayer?"
Kayer clearly disagreed with Nisi's statement. He looked paler than usual, and his claws were deeply embedded in Sasalin's back, drawing blood from the Slakor, but Sasalin clearly didn't care. Nevertheless, Sasalin realized he had scared his new friend and landed in an open space.
"Sorry, sorry, I smelled something. I need to take care of it!"
"You had to drag us along too?" Tenuk climbed down from Sasalin's back, sliding to the ground along the tail, and asked sharply. "We left Retvik! We abandoned that strong, aggressive big guy! How is he supposed to find us?"
"He'll figure it out..." Nisi nodded. "Retvik is slow, but not stupid."
"Can Retvik drive a car?"
Nisi blinked her eyes and turned to look at Tenuk. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a car? He doesn't have a truck like yours, and I've never seen him drive a cute little car like Kayer's. He started driving to work purely because you always drove us to work. He only has a bicycle."
A laugh interrupted them. Sasalin suddenly burst into laughter, but no one knew what he was laughing at. Sasalin took a long time to calm down.
"Sorry, sorry, I just imagined it—your big, armored friend riding a small bicycle designed for Temson children. The image was just too funny! I wish I had telepathy. This idea was so amusing! I have to keep it dear."
Kayer also laughed because he could imagine what Sasalin was thinking. "Well, well. But what did you smell? Why did you fly so fast?"
Sasalin grunted, took off, and disappeared quickly, then flew back and left a body in front of Nisi. It was an Oroslak, a very rare golden-white dragon-like creature. But its head was missing. "Another one is dead. I heard their cries. I smelled their blood. I must protect them and hunt down the killer. This is Isini's command. Those creatures are nearby."
The powerful Slakor suddenly froze. Nisi and Kayer also froze, their attention drawn to a gap at the edge of the clearing. A huge and dark creature was staring at them, hissing. This creature suddenly spread its two pairs of massive wings and rushed forward, its target locked on Sasalin, completely ignoring the three small figures between it and Sasalin. Kayer and Tenuk barely managed to dodge aside, but Nisi found herself pulled to the ground, almost thrown onto Sasalin.
Sasalin grabbed Nisi, used his long and agile tail to throw her onto his back, and then took off into the air. The black creature with two pairs of wings quickly gave chase.
Kayer grunted, pulled out a gun from behind him, and then opened the bag to take out a belt of bullets. He hung the bullet belt around his chest for easy access, but soon realized that Nisi, Sasalin, and the monster were all gone.
"Hey, Tenuk, can you transform into a flying animal?" Kayer asked.
"Do you want to chase after them?"
"Nonsense."
"But... one of them is a giant monster!"
"So what? My rifle here has strong firepower and I can shoot at any time. I just need to see it, and I can bring it down."
Tenuk hesitated for a moment, then took a step back, giving himself some space. With a low, slightly painful groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turned into scales, and his arms became wings. He quickly transformed into an ordinary light blue Slakor, but his eyes remained red.
"Come on up."
Tunuk now looked like an ordinary Slak, with neatly arranged scales on his back and a pair of spikes, making it easier for Kayer to grab. Tunuk took a long time to get off the ground, but once he was airborne, he quickly adjusted his direction and tried to catch up.
However, Tunuk and Kayer soon realized they were not facing just one opponent. A second dark monster burst out from below them, and Tunuk barely dodged the collision.
"I guess this is the other terrible big monster that Larenex was worried about?" Kayer frowned, trying to shoot at the second monster, but missed. He quickly reloaded.
Tunuk didn't respond; he was busy flying toward Nisi and Sasalin, even though another monster was chasing them. Kayer clumsily turned around to face the monster. The monster was chasing them, and Kayer thought it was a good sign because he could aim and shoot more easily. Two bullets pierced the monster's upper wing, and it painfully roared before disappearing into the forest. Kayer wasn't sure if it was still following them, but he felt it probably couldn't keep up anymore.
Up ahead, Sasalin was wildly flailing his body, spitting fire at the black monster, while Nisi desperately held onto Sasalin to prevent him from falling. Although this monster was clearly injured, it seemed enraged and unwilling to retreat, and the fireballs seemed to do little damage. After stabilizing himself, Nisi took out his trusted shotgun. Of course, a shotgun wouldn't be effective against such a monster, but the spread bullets at least might scare off this black beast?
